WEBVTT

NOTE Paragraph

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.505
(laughter, applause)

00:00:12.505 --> 00:00:13.714
MARISHA: I want mine.

00:00:14.284 --> 00:00:16.263
TRAVIS: Do you not know who we are?

00:00:19.473 --> 00:00:21.212
LAURA: That’s okay, we’ll stand!

00:00:21.212 --> 00:00:22.813
MARISHA: Travis needs the end.

00:00:22.813 --> 00:00:24.017
TALIESIN: There we are.

00:00:31.747 --> 00:00:34.194
TRAVIS: This is my blessing. This is my curse.

00:00:34.194 --> 00:00:36.933
(laughter)

00:00:36.933 --> 00:00:38.762
MATT: Got to plug it in first.

00:00:38.762 --> 00:00:41.093
LAURA: This is so official. I don’t know--

00:00:41.093 --> 00:00:42.194
TRAVIS: Are these on?

00:00:42.194 --> 00:00:44.658
LAURA: --feels like we’re about to have a
meeting.

00:00:44.658 --> 00:00:47.013
(laughter)

00:00:47.013 --> 00:00:48.853
MARISHA: I guess you guys want to share a mic?

00:00:50.503 --> 00:00:55.572
(laughter)

00:00:58.222 --> 00:00:59.440
MATT: There we go.

00:00:59.440 --> 00:01:00.251
SAM: Hi!

00:01:00.251 --> 00:01:00.912
AUDIENCE: Hi!

00:01:02.752 --> 00:01:07.642
MATT: I’m not going to lie, this is impressive to
me. For a Sunday at noon panel at any convention,

00:01:07.642 --> 00:01:09.585
this many people is a feat.

00:01:09.585 --> 00:01:11.608
(laughter)

00:01:11.608 --> 00:01:12.242
SAM: Welcome.

00:01:13.032 --> 00:01:13.906
LAURA: What is happening?

00:01:13.906 --> 00:01:14.614
MARISHA: I’m making--

00:01:14.614 --> 00:01:16.343
AUDIENCE MEMBER: Form Voltron!

00:01:16.343 --> 00:01:18.732
(laughter)

00:01:20.472 --> 00:01:22.756
MATT: This is the entire panel. Just watching this
happen.

00:01:22.756 --> 00:01:26.264
(laughter)

00:01:29.694 --> 00:01:30.764
MATT: So, hey guys!

00:01:30.764 --> 00:01:31.396
AUDIENCE: Hi!

00:01:34.736 --> 00:01:39.993
MATT: We are-- she likes your hair.

00:01:39.993 --> 00:01:41.583
LAURA: I like your hair.

00:01:42.493 --> 00:01:43.583
MATT: This is the panel.

00:01:43.583 --> 00:01:47.532
(laughter)

00:01:47.532 --> 00:01:49.526
MARISHA: Miming into mics and complimenting
people.

00:01:49.526 --> 00:01:55.264
(laughter and applause)

00:01:56.194 --> 00:01:57.471
LAURA: Did you need to get any taller?

00:01:57.471 --> 00:01:57.983
TRAVIS: Overwatch.

00:01:59.243 --> 00:02:06.426
MATT: (whispery ominous voice) Be careful he’s
watching. (normal voice) We are all actors. We

00:02:06.426 --> 00:02:11.213
also are part of a online D&amp;D game called Critical
Role--

00:02:11.213 --> 00:02:15.055
(cheering)

00:02:15.755 --> 00:02:21.061
MATT: Where we play Dungeons &amp; Dragons every week
on Twitch with Geek &amp; Sundry. That’s <i>not</i> what

00:02:21.061 --> 00:02:22.575
this panel’s about!

00:02:22.575 --> 00:02:29.342
MARISHA: I mean, it could be what it’s about. It
kind of is. We’re not going to stop it. We’d kind

00:02:29.342 --> 00:02:31.134
of rather talk about D&amp;D.

00:02:31.134 --> 00:02:32.144
LAURA: No! That’s not true.

00:02:32.144 --> 00:02:33.184
MATT: That’s not true at all.

00:02:34.234 --> 00:02:36.026
MARISHA: <i>I’d</i> rather talk about D&amp;D.

00:02:36.026 --> 00:02:37.332
(laughter)

00:02:37.332 --> 00:02:38.493
MARISHA: I’ll speak for myself.

00:02:39.523 --> 00:02:45.263
MATT: The main topics of this panel will be-- the
theme of it is voiceover and animation, video

00:02:45.263 --> 00:02:49.465
games in general. World of voiceover, our
experiences there, and your questions regarding

00:02:49.465 --> 00:02:54.614
that bit of silliness. But, you are also free to
slip in D&amp;D-related questions, should you feel

00:02:54.614 --> 00:02:59.540
driven to do so. But first, let’s begin with
introductions. Let’s go ahead and talk a little

00:02:59.540 --> 00:03:02.513
bit about ourselves and what we do, starting with
Travis Willingham!

00:03:02.513 --> 00:03:11.544
TRAVIS: Hi, I’m Travis Willingham. I’m a Leo. I
play a goliath barbarian on Critical Role named

00:03:11.544 --> 00:03:20.025
Grog. I’ve done lots of animes like Fullmetal
Alchemist and Ouran Host Club and stuff like that.

00:03:20.025 --> 00:03:25.823
Lots of video games. Last year was Halo 5:
Guardians. A couple of other things. I like to

00:03:25.823 --> 00:03:27.403
talk into mics for fun! Woo!

00:03:27.403 --> 00:03:32.606
(applause)

00:03:34.756 --> 00:03:36.909
TALIESIN: Hi, my name is Taliesin Jaffe.

00:03:36.909 --> 00:03:42.499
(cheering)

00:03:42.499 --> 00:03:48.389
TALIESIN: You don’t have to clap, but that was
nice. I play the human gunslinger Percival

00:03:48.389 --> 00:03:54.268
Fredrickstein Von Musel Klossowski de Rolo the
Third on Twitch on Thursdays. But other than that,

00:03:54.268 --> 00:04:01.677
I also like to talk into microphones. You can hear
me in lots of animes, most recently Black Butler:

00:04:01.677 --> 00:04:05.731
Book of Murder, which is coming out in a couple of
months. Black butlers.

00:04:05.731 --> 00:04:07.809
(laughter)

00:04:07.809 --> 00:04:12.799
TALIESIN: And lots of video games. Final Fantasy
IV, Street Fighter IV, World of Warcraft.

00:04:15.479 --> 00:04:25.437
MARISHA: Hello, I am Marisha Ray. I play the
half-elven druid Keyleth on Critical Role. And I

00:04:25.437 --> 00:04:32.729
also talk into microphones, like everybody else,
and like I am currently. In Metal Gear Phantom

00:04:32.729 --> 00:04:41.638
Pain, Star Wars Battlefront. Just came out, Fire
Emblem: Fates, which half of us are in. You can

00:04:41.638 --> 00:04:46.760
also watch Super Power Beat Down, which is a show
that I host, because I sometimes also talk into cameras.

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:51.045
(cheering)

00:04:52.235 --> 00:04:58.584
LAURA: Hi, I’m Laura Bailey. Oh my gosh, I’m a
Gemini, which is actually kind of cool because I

00:04:58.584 --> 00:05:00.505
am a twin on Critical Role as well.

00:05:02.465 --> 00:05:06.684
I play the half-elven ranger Vex'ahlia and
I have a bear named Trinket.

00:05:06.684 --> 00:05:08.366
MATT: (bear sounds)

00:05:08.366 --> 00:05:14.685
LAURA: Thank you. Thank you, Trinket. I guess in
the last, what, the last year? Halo 5: Guardians.

00:05:14.685 --> 00:05:24.330
Street Fighter 5. Avengers Assemble. Uncharted 4,
coming up.

00:05:24.330 --> 00:05:28.480
(cheering, applause)

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:44.560
SAM: Hi. I'm Sam Riegel, I've lost my voice. My
sign is Libra. Very measured and even-keeled. I

00:05:44.560 --> 00:05:57.405
play Scanlan Shorthalt, the bard gnome on Critical
Role. I also act in things sometimes and I don't

00:05:57.405 --> 00:06:07.473
know what I’ve done. I did some Teenage Mutant
Ninja Turtles for a while. I was Spiderman in

00:06:07.473 --> 00:06:15.414
Spiderman games. I was in Persona as the little
annoying Teddie. Other things too, I die in a lot

00:06:15.414 --> 00:06:25.464
of games. Any game that Laura is killing things
in, I'm also dying in. I also started directing

00:06:25.464 --> 00:06:33.554
stuff too. So I direct voices for animation and
for Disney. In fact I'm going to be directing Matt

00:06:33.554 --> 00:06:35.864
Mercer tomorrow at 9:00AM.

00:06:38.234 --> 00:06:39.715
MATT: Thanks for the reminder.

00:06:40.755 --> 00:06:45.095
MARISHA: I love how they act like you were getting
called into the principal's office. Like ooh, snap!

00:06:47.715 --> 00:06:49.974
MATT: At least my character voices aren't
high-pitched tomorrow.

00:06:50.664 --> 00:06:51.384
LAURA: Mine are.

00:06:52.464 --> 00:06:54.735
SAM: One of them's like Mickey Mouse range.

00:06:54.735 --> 00:06:55.861
MATT: I was being ironic.

00:06:58.191 --> 00:07:00.285
SAM: (high-pitched noise) That’s fun!

00:07:01.485 --> 00:07:12.355
MATT: Hi, my name is Matthew Mercer. I'm Dungeon
Master. I'm a Cancer. That's not my sign, that's

00:07:12.355 --> 00:07:21.634
my self-esteem. "I'm a cancer!" I also talk into
microphones for a living. Cartoons, video games.

00:07:21.634 --> 00:07:23.444
Leon Kennedy in Resident Evil.

00:07:24.964 --> 00:07:26.354
LAURA: Oh yeah, we were a pair.

00:07:26.354 --> 00:07:28.743
MATT: Yeah! What's up? How's my hair look?

00:07:28.743 --> 00:07:32.729
SAM: You both killed me, I'm sure. (zombie noise)

00:07:32.729 --> 00:07:41.311
MATT: Recent-ish stuff, there's Fallout 4. I was
MacCready. Fire Emblem: Fates, which just came out

00:07:41.311 --> 00:07:46.320
also. I was Ryoma as well as a few other
characters. Yeah, so that's our introduction...

00:07:46.320 --> 00:07:48.209
and that's our panel. Thanks guys for coming!

00:07:48.209 --> 00:07:51.349
(laughter)

00:07:51.349 --> 00:07:56.488
MATT: Let's go ahead and kick this off with a
little bit of Q&amp;A. If you're not sick of us by now

00:07:56.488 --> 00:08:00.889
this weekend, let's see if we can make this happen
soon. You sir at the very front, go bring your

00:08:00.889 --> 00:08:02.337
question to the microphone.

00:08:02.337 --> 00:08:10.457
AUDIENCE MEMBER: Hi guys. Apparently the mic's a
little hot still. I'll just stand right here. Hi

00:08:10.457 --> 00:08:15.269
guys, Law Johnson, Facebook's Dungeons &amp; Dragons
Memes, awesome to see you again. I hope you guys

00:08:15.269 --> 00:08:19.961
are having a super fun time in Portland and thank
you on behalf of all Portland Critters for

00:08:19.961 --> 00:08:29.797
bringing your magic to our weird city. (Grog
voice) I would like to ask a question.

00:08:29.797 --> 00:08:34.760
(normal voice) I'm going to be that guy and-- right out
the gate-- start with a D&amp;D question because my

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:39.050
fans will kill me if I don't. It has a little bit
to do with acting so that's something. In a

00:08:39.050 --> 00:08:44.411
hypothetical scenario in which they make a Vox
Machina live-action movie, which professional

00:08:44.411 --> 00:08:47.768
actor that was not yourself would you choose to
play your character?

00:08:50.478 --> 00:08:51.758
MATT: That's a great question.

00:08:53.488 --> 00:08:54.918
SAM: Arnold Schwarzenegger.

00:08:56.448 --> 00:08:57.532
AUDIENCE MEMBER: Dave Bautista!

00:08:58.193 --> 00:08:59.953
TRAVIS: Dave Bautista would be Grog!

00:09:03.473 --> 00:09:04.603
SAM: Dinklage, for me.

00:09:04.603 --> 00:09:14.630
(cheering, applause)

00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:17.446
MARISHA: We were toying around with Zooey
Deschanel for Keyleth?

00:09:17.446 --> 00:09:19.496
(noises of agreement)

00:09:19.496 --> 00:09:20.703
TALIESIN: We've had this conversation.

00:09:20.703 --> 00:09:22.953
LAURA: Maybe like Kate Beckinsale or something.

00:09:26.723 --> 00:09:28.492
MATT: Kate Beckinsale, yeah! I can see that.

00:09:28.492 --> 00:09:29.324
MARISHA: She's hot.

00:09:29.324 --> 00:09:32.603
TALIESIN: Is it Hugh Dancy from Hannibal who plays
Will Graham?

00:09:35.753 --> 00:09:37.161
MATT: Who do you want for Vax?

00:09:37.161 --> 00:09:38.982
SAM: Oh, what about Gilmore?

00:09:40.282 --> 00:09:43.152
LAURA: Oh, oh! Somebody posted something on
Twitter and it was like, "Oh my god, he's

00:09:43.152 --> 00:09:46.851
perfect". It was the guy who played Sayid on Lost.

00:09:46.851 --> 00:09:48.601
MATT: Yeah! Oh, he'd be phenomenal.

00:09:48.601 --> 00:09:49.641
LAURA: Or he'd be <i>dreamy</i>.

00:09:50.461 --> 00:09:55.102
MATT: Or, also the guy who plays Oberyn on Game of
Thrones.

00:09:56.472 --> 00:10:00.511
MARISHA: Ooh, yeah, I agree with that.

00:10:02.731 --> 00:10:05.972
MATT: Man or woman, you had to agree, Oberyn had
it going on.

00:10:07.742 --> 00:10:08.961
AUDIENCE MEMBER: Awesome, thank you guys.

00:10:08.961 --> 00:10:10.342
MATT: Good question, thank you.

00:10:10.342 --> 00:10:14.762
(applause)

00:10:16.212 --> 00:10:19.253
SAM: Oh, and Trinket would be played by the bear
from The Revenant.

00:10:19.268 --> 00:10:23.718
(laughter)

00:10:23.723 --> 00:10:27.142
MATT: I'm so glad that guy's getting work again.

00:10:27.142 --> 00:10:28.593
SAM: Ah yes, go ahead.

00:10:31.503 --> 00:10:37.590
AUDIENCE MEMBER: What is your favorite voice to
ever do when you do voice acting? Also, never have

00:10:37.590 --> 00:10:45.276
Travis play a fighter attached with a rogue. It's
400 points of damage a round.

00:10:49.486 --> 00:10:52.612
TRAVIS: You said numbers. I don't understand.

00:10:54.252 --> 00:10:57.352
MATT: All right, so favorite voice you've ever
performed.

00:10:59.242 --> 00:11:00.922
TRAVIS: Start that way this time.

00:11:05.212 --> 00:11:06.632
SAM: No wait, that's you Matt, you start.

00:11:06.632 --> 00:11:08.301
MATT: No no please, go ahead.

00:11:10.501 --> 00:11:13.902
LAURA: Why does it feel like it's so early and
it's noon now?

00:11:13.902 --> 00:11:19.271
TRAVIS: We're all going to give the answer like,
"It's like trying to pick between your children.

00:11:19.271 --> 00:11:21.783
"You just can't have one favorite."

00:11:28.483 --> 00:11:34.706
SAM: I did the voice of Starscream a couple times.
That was really fun and it was horrifyingly bad on

00:11:34.706 --> 00:11:41.776
your vocal cords. It was fun to do. What about
you, Matt?

00:11:43.436 --> 00:11:46.458
MATT: There's one project I can't talk about right
now but I'm really excited about.

00:11:46.458 --> 00:11:48.447
TRAVIS: Do it anyway, violate your NDA!

00:11:48.447 --> 00:11:55.877
MATT: No. I will say from a personality
standpoint, I really really personally enjoyed

00:11:55.877 --> 00:12:05.647
Aloth in Pillars of Eternity. (Aloth voice) "Just
a sort of very slightly nervous elven wizard who

00:12:05.647 --> 00:12:11.467
has an issue wherein his body actually contains
two souls and one happens to be this ancient woman

00:12:11.467 --> 00:12:15.461
named Iselmyr who creeps out on occasion but not
really to--" (Iselmyr voice) “get really angry at

00:12:15.461 --> 00:12:23.436
people! Shut up you fucking cocksmith!" (Aloth
voice) "I'm terribly sorry. That wasn't me. That

00:12:23.436 --> 00:12:25.576
was Iselmyr. Please don't hit me."

00:12:29.466 --> 00:12:33.488
TALIESIN: PCB let me Ed Wynn for a video game
once.

00:12:34.238 --> 00:12:37.276
MARISHA: I love your Ed Wynn. It is so cool.

00:12:37.276 --> 00:12:39.739
TALIESIN: I was like, "Can I do the Ed Wynn for
this game cause no one's ever going to play this

00:12:39.739 --> 00:12:43.712
game?" They're like, "Yeah sure." (Ed Wynn voice)
So the entire game I get to play a villain who

00:12:43.712 --> 00:12:47.288
talks like this. It's absolutely fantastic.

00:12:49.488 --> 00:12:56.086
MARISHA: That's such a good Ed Wynn. I guess here
recently in Fire Emblem Fates (Effie voice) "I'm

00:12:56.086 --> 00:13:05.816
Effie who's a bro'd out, testosterone-pumping,
giant sword-wielding chick. I’m really obsessed

00:13:05.816 --> 00:13:11.576
with food all the time. So I got to do this all
the time and that was really great. She's really

00:13:11.576 --> 00:13:16.508
great." What's actually been really fun is I have
somebody-- cause, you know, in those games you

00:13:16.508 --> 00:13:22.473
tend to do two or three characters-- so I'm also
Oboro which is one of my Keyleth-y voice. and

00:13:22.473 --> 00:13:27.565
someone was like, "Marisha, you were great in Fire
Emblem: Fates. Oboro is amazing. I don't know who

00:13:27.565 --> 00:13:39.137
they got to do a voice for Effie, though." I was
like, "Hahaha!" and let it go.

00:13:41.237 --> 00:13:42.807
LAURA: That's terrible! I would cry.

00:13:45.477 --> 00:13:49.402
LAURA: Gosh I don't know. I think one of the most
fun times I ever had recording was for Shin-chan.

00:13:50.747 --> 00:13:52.620
MARISHA: One of my personal favorites of yours.

00:13:52.620 --> 00:13:56.732
LAURA: (Shin-chan voice) Thank you so much. Yeah,
cause I just talked like I had a potato in my

00:13:56.732 --> 00:14:05.451
throat the whole time. Any shame I had was pretty
much left at the door. Travis, you didn't answer!

00:14:05.451 --> 00:14:15.011
TRAVIS: Oh shit. (Gazlowe voice) I like playing
Gazlowe. He's this really high character and he's

00:14:15.011 --> 00:14:17.620
a jerk so, you know. He talks like this!

00:14:21.480 --> 00:14:22.593
MATT: Good question.

00:14:24.533 --> 00:14:30.182
AUDIENCE MEMBER: I wanted to know, on the day that
one of our beloved player characters happens to pass.

00:14:30.182 --> 00:14:30.781
LAURA: No!

00:14:30.781 --> 00:14:31.850
TRAVIS: You shut your mouth!

00:14:33.730 --> 00:14:40.281
AUDIENCE MEMBER: Whether due to heroism or, in
Vax's case, impatience. Just wondering, what were

00:14:40.281 --> 00:14:42.652
your ideas for your next player character?

00:14:44.512 --> 00:14:50.010
MARISHA: Like 80 people in the audience go...
"We've all thought about this."

00:14:51.770 --> 00:14:57.220
TALIESIN: I don't want to spoil. I'm not going to
lie, I've got very complicated ideas about this.

00:14:57.225 --> 00:14:58.505
TRAVIS: You do?!

00:14:58.510 --> 00:15:01.821
TALIESIN: I've spent time thinking about what
I'm going to do when I finally fuck up.

00:15:02.601 --> 00:15:06.256
MATT: It is interesting. There's an aspect of
surprising you guys with whatever character they

00:15:06.256 --> 00:15:10.581
come up with. But whatever you feel like sharing.
You don't have to be specific, but you can be somewhat--

00:15:10.581 --> 00:15:13.671
TALIESIN: I like your Blood Hunter class, that's
what I'll share.

00:15:18.521 --> 00:15:26.262
MARISHA: I've thought about it. I've got a few
ideas. I have an idea for a bard that would be the

00:15:26.262 --> 00:15:33.944
whole opposite of Scanlan. I don't want to reveal
it too much.

00:15:33.944 --> 00:15:42.904
SAM: Well, I was going to come back as a druid
named Meyleth. It's going to be awesome.

00:15:42.904 --> 00:15:53.451
LAURA: I was thinking I was going to come back as
a tiefling, but I don't know, Zahra is so freaking cool.

00:15:53.718 --> 00:15:55.468
SAM: She’s not the only tiefling in the world.

00:15:55.468 --> 00:16:02.019
LAURA: Yeah, I know, but they're supposed to be
rare, right? So I might change it. I really want

00:16:02.019 --> 00:16:11.846
to be somebody with blue hair. I have ideas. A
were-bear with blue hair. That's going to be my name!

00:16:11.846 --> 00:16:22.937
TRAVIS: I was going to come back as Helga the
human bar wench and try to die as fast as

00:16:22.937 --> 00:16:25.597
possible. It's a horrible decision.

00:16:25.597 --> 00:16:34.458
MATT: We'll have to get Kit to do the art for the
one ten minute period she actually plays in the

00:16:34.458 --> 00:16:44.117
game. That's pretty funny, actually. I'll have to
kill you first. Hi, what you got?

00:16:45.497 --> 00:16:49.192
AUDIENCE MEMBER: So, Laura, if you want to play
someone with blue hair, you could always do a

00:16:49.192 --> 00:17:08.875
water genasi. Also, go Geminis. My question is to
all of you, it's a D&amp;D question. Vox Machina's

00:17:09.104 --> 00:17:16.905
obviously made up of a lot of very diverse
personalities and people with very different ways

00:17:16.905 --> 00:17:22.958
of looking about things, going about goals that
sometimes may not always exactly line up with each

00:17:22.958 --> 00:17:33.344
other. So what are your guys' strategies--and
Matt, what are your strategies as a DM--for making

00:17:33.344 --> 00:17:46.286
sure that all of your characters are still
working towards the same goal and keeping

00:17:46.286 --> 00:17:51.641
things amicable while at the same time staying
true to your characters?

00:17:53.771 --> 00:17:59.574
TALIESIN: We have a Fight Club on set. We can't
talk about it.

00:18:05.228 --> 00:18:10.131
LAURA: I think that's one of the most fun things
about playing is that everybody has their own

00:18:10.131 --> 00:18:19.414
moral code and we're trying to make that all mesh
together to the same goal. If we think, as our

00:18:19.414 --> 00:18:33.094
character, that something's okay and Keyleth
definitely does not, then I think that's fine, to

00:18:33.094 --> 00:18:38.862
see how that plays out and see why somebody would
have a problem with somebody else's actions.

00:18:39.472 --> 00:18:48.123
MARISHA: Yeah, amicable is hard because we all do
have our personal goals that we're thinking of all

00:18:48.123 --> 00:18:53.194
the time. And... being someone with a moral
compass is very difficult.

00:18:54.674 --> 00:19:00.242
LAURA: Vex is a really good person! She's a really
good person. Don't you shake your head.

00:19:00.242 --> 00:19:01.472
(laughter)

00:19:01.472 --> 00:19:04.482
MARISHA: She's saying it for herself,
I'm pretty sure.

00:19:06.442 --> 00:19:09.773
TALIESIN: We snicker about it backstage when we're
done. We're like, "Oh wow, that was intense."

00:19:11.493 --> 00:19:22.391
MARISHA: We love it. It's hard to answer. Right
before the dragons, there was a moment where I was

00:19:22.391 --> 00:19:30.663
like, "I don't know. I'm having a hard time
justifying Keyleth staying around." Because there

00:19:30.663 --> 00:19:37.112
was a lot of animosity in the group. It's funny
how things can turn out like petty little

00:19:37.112 --> 00:19:39.253
squabbles after the world is burning to the
ground.

00:19:41.253 --> 00:19:47.343
MATT: Which plays into my answer as well. I don't
want to drive the players to a specific goal or

00:19:47.343 --> 00:19:53.663
shoehorn them in. Let them play in their field. I
love inter-party conflict. For those who saw the

00:19:53.663 --> 00:20:04.563
Percy-Grog standoff, I was mentally eating popcorn
the entire time.

00:20:04.563 --> 00:20:06.711
(laughter)

00:20:06.711 --> 00:20:08.082
MATT: It was awesome.

00:20:08.492 --> 00:20:09.871
TALIESIN: I was so ready for that.

00:20:09.871 --> 00:20:11.282
(laughter)

00:20:11.282 --> 00:20:15.653
MATT: I love inter-party conflict, and I never
want to dissuade players from that. If characters

00:20:15.653 --> 00:20:18.573
have to leave for a while from the game, that's
totally fine too. They can play a different

00:20:18.573 --> 00:20:23.482
character for a while, and when they feel the
other character wants to return, they can. Or if

00:20:23.482 --> 00:20:27.312
the other character ends up becoming an antagonist
to the party that's also a cool twist. I've had

00:20:27.312 --> 00:20:31.013
that happen in previous games, where all of a
sudden, a player character got so fed up with the

00:20:31.013 --> 00:20:35.083
party they left, and they came back six months
down the line as an antagonist to the party,

00:20:35.083 --> 00:20:39.774
trying to stop them from making such poor
decisions in the future. Then they became a DM

00:20:39.774 --> 00:20:42.282
controlled character, and the person was fighting
against their old character!

00:20:42.282 --> 00:20:44.582
(laughter)

00:20:46.722 --> 00:20:49.951
MATT: So, I love watching the dynamic happen and I
don't want to dissuade players from finding their

00:20:49.951 --> 00:20:54.043
characters out and work with them to whatever the
ramifications of those discussions are.

00:20:55.493 --> 00:20:55.992
AUDIENCE MEMBER: Thank you.

