00:35:31.547 --> 00:35:38.257
AUDIENCE MEMBER: I had a personal question for all
of you. There’s this thing that happens sometimes

00:35:38.257 --> 00:35:48.207
when you’re an artist, where you have a lot of
self-doubt. When did you identify yourself as a

00:35:48.207 --> 00:35:52.798
voice actor? Was there a moment? Is there a little
story or a snip or a time where you were like,

00:35:52.798 --> 00:35:55.907
“Yeah, I think I just did it.”

00:35:55.907 --> 00:35:58.117
MARISHA: You guys, I think I made it.

00:35:58.117 --> 00:35:59.978
(laughter)

00:35:59.978 --> 00:36:05.658
MARISHA: Yeah, that’s hard because we’re always
still working to keep going. You can’t ever stop

00:36:05.658 --> 00:36:10.963
working. So none of us-- I don’t think any of us
are just like, “Yeah! We can stop now.”

00:36:10.963 --> 00:36:16.918
AUDIENCE MEMBER: I don’t mean “You can stop,” or
“I’m done. I’ve hit the peak,” but the moment you

00:36:16.918 --> 00:36:23.257
go from thinking of yourself as a squib to being
“I am actually an actor.”

00:36:23.257 --> 00:36:24.857
TALIESIN: If I hit it, I’ll let you know.

00:36:24.857 --> 00:36:26.518
(laughter)

00:36:26.518 --> 00:36:30.658
MATT: I think the closest thing I can say is the
moment that I quit my day job, after saving up for

00:36:30.658 --> 00:36:38.516
months to downsize to a tiny apartment and decide
that this was-- it’s now or never. Before I had

00:36:38.516 --> 00:36:43.539
the regrets of never really trying. I’m going to
put all of my power and energy into this, and go

00:36:43.539 --> 00:36:46.928
through the hardships. If it doesn’t work out, at
least I can live the rest of my life knowing that

00:36:46.928 --> 00:36:51.178
I gave it a shot, as opposed to wondering what
could’ve been. And so, though it wasn’t--

00:36:51.178 --> 00:36:53.956
(applause)

00:36:53.956 --> 00:36:58.187
MATT: It wasn’t an easy time. And it was a very
prolonged piece of time of not getting peace and

00:36:58.187 --> 00:37:02.588
time, but I think taking that big enough step to
go ahead and try for a passion like that was the

00:37:02.588 --> 00:37:04.868
moment where I was like, “Now I’m an actor.
Because I’m poor.”

00:37:04.868 --> 00:37:06.908
(laughter)

00:37:06.908 --> 00:37:15.478
LAURA: Yeah. You have that moment of being able to
not have another job and just your acting job.

00:37:15.478 --> 00:37:18.318
That’s when you go, “Okay. This is something I can
actually--”

00:37:18.318 --> 00:37:22.778
TALIESIN: When you cut down all of your expenses
to the point of which, you’re like, “Okay. Now I can live.”

00:37:22.778 --> 00:37:29.447
MARISHA: “Now I can survive.” Yeah. I found that,
as time goes on, and as I keep working, that I’m

00:37:29.447 --> 00:37:35.327
having a harder and harder time just identifying
with any one thing. I can’t <i>just</i> call myself a

00:37:35.327 --> 00:37:41.016
voice actor, because a lot of us, we’re directors,
writers, producers--

00:37:41.016 --> 00:37:42.497
TALIESIN: Professional D&amp;D players.

00:37:42.497 --> 00:37:49.528
MARISHA: Professional D&amp;D players. So I kind of
feel that saying voice acting-- and this goes for

00:37:49.528 --> 00:37:56.799
any artists out there-- don’t adhere to it so much
that you end up limiting yourself in the long run,

00:37:56.799 --> 00:38:01.372
because it can bleed into other areas.

00:38:01.372 --> 00:38:02.727
(applause)

